{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|Астафьева, Серафима Александровна|date=November 2016}}
[[File:Serafina Astafieva c. 1890s.jpg|thumbnail|Serafina Astafieva, c. 1890s]]
'''Serafina Astafieva''' (Russian: Серафима Александровна Астафьева; 1876 &ndash; 13 September 1934) was a Russian dancer and ballet teacher.<ref name=OX>''Oxford Dictionary of Dance'' (2004) [[Oxford University Press]]</ref>

Astafieva was a pupil at the [[Bolshoi Kamenny Theatre]] School and in 1895 graduated from the [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Mariinsky Ballet School]]. In 1896 she married [[Jozef Kshessinsky]] a famous [[character dancer]]. From 1909-1911 Astafieva performed with [[Sergei Diaghilev]]'s [[Ballets Russes]]. After retiring from performing she opened the Russian Dancing Academy at [[The Pheasantry]] on [[King's Road]] in [[Chelsea, London]]. Her pupils included [[Anton Dolin]], [[Margot Fonteyn]],<ref name=OX/> [[Alicia Markova]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/03/arts/dance/03markova.html Alicia Markova, Ballerina Known for Giselle, Dies at 94] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> and [[Hermione Darnborough]].<ref>''Dancing Times'', July 2009</ref>

A [[blue plaque]] unveiled in 1968 commemorates Astafieva at 152 [[King's Road]] in Chelsea.<ref name='EngHet'>{{cite web|url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/discover/blue-plaques/search/astafieva-princess-seraphine-1876-1934|title=ASTAFIEVA, PRINCESS SERAPHINE (1876-1934)|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=2012-08-18}}</ref>

She is referenced as "Grishkin" in T. S. Eliot's poem ''[[Whispers of Immortality]]''.

